{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5d5db508-cdaf-4e1f-a726-7a5e74677e00","content":"In .NET MAUI, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n    {\n#if ANDROID\n        events.AddAndroid(android => android\n            .OnPause(activity => { /* app pausing */ })\n            .OnStop(activity => { /* app stopped */ }));\n#elif IOS\n        events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* entered background */ }));\n#endif\n    });\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\nEach platform exposes its native events (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`) through the same pattern. The delegates receive the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS) so you can interact with platform APIs directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4a47f95d-0b0a-40a4-b0df-10c2068db21e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI, specifically:\n- Android: OnPause/OnStop\n- iOS: DidEnterBackground\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase, as this is a general programming question rather than a codebase-specific one.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, you can hook into platform-specific lifecycle events using the `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` method in your `MauiProgram.cs`. This uses the `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` namespace.\n\n\nNow I'll walk through the implementation with a code example showing how to register handlers for these specific lifecycle events on each platform.","outputTokens":441,"requestId":"0839:3596A1:A4129D:BDD214:69F2A846"},"id":"e3f233ad-2702-497a-9109-ce470448e38a","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:54:38.974Z","pa